<h2>Gravity Furnace</h2>
<p>
A gravity furnace is effictively a big upside-down bucket full of fire
with a vent out the back. The heat travels up on the way to the exhaust,
which heats the bucket. The cold air outside then warms, rising due to
gravity, clearing the way for more cold air. An alternative to this
is a forced-air furnace like in central-air homes.
</p>
<a data-flickr-embed="true"  href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/40925843@N03/24906476465/in/dateposted-public/" title="IMG_20160206_201046"><img src="https://farm2.staticflickr.com/1656/24906476465_20ba95b080.jpg" width="375" height="500" alt="IMG_20160206_201046"></a>
<p>
This was the easiest to get running - with
a one pound portable bottle and a regulator, a little cleaning of the
propane inlet, breaking the pilot light window free of rust, and it runs.
After this photo, I later enameled some outer surfaces black. Also shook
a few ancient wasp nests out of the exhaust.
</p>

